<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<rules>

  <rule name="Do not redirect SharePoint paths" enabled="true" stopProcessing="true">
    <match url="^(sites|SitePages|_layouts|_api|_vti_bin)(/.*)?$" ignoreCase="true" />
    <action type="None" />
  </rule>

  <rule name="Redirect root only" enabled="true" stopProcessing="true">
    <match url="^$" />
    <conditions logicalGrouping="MatchAll" trackAllCaptures="false">
      <add input="{HTTP_HOST}" pattern="^ngau-portal-stg\.au\.myngc\.com$" />
    </conditions>
    <action type="Redirect"
            url="https://ngapac.sharepoint.com/"
            appendQueryString="false"
            redirectType="Found" />
  </rule>

</rules>



The original setup was redirecting too broadly because the rule matched **everything** with `url=".*"` and then captured the full path using `PATH_INFO` / `{C:1}`, so IIS treated `/sites/anysite`, `/SitePages/Home.aspx`, and other SharePoint paths as valid redirect targets and sent them across to `ngapac.sharepoint.com`. We fixed it by replacing that broad rule with a **root-only redirect**: only the bare host/root URL is allowed to redirect, while anything after the slash is left alone so the old SharePoint/IIS paths can still load. The last bit of confusion was browser caching from the earlier redirect behaviour, likely made worse if it had been tested as a permanent redirect, which is why adding `?nocache=12345` proved the server rule was now working correctly.

